        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-06-25T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-06-25T02:00:00-05:00" n="465" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d465">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893–50 Recovery/6–2548: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-06-25T16:00:00+09:00">June 25, 1948—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 25—8:09 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1149. In light Cleveland–Gilpatric telephone conversation and discussion with ECA
                    Mission here June 25, Embassy has agreed best wording article IV, paragraph 4 is
                    first sentence recommended for paragraph 4 in <hi rend="smallcaps">Toeca</hi> 31
                    of June 11 and so presented in <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> today.
                    Embassy likewise now supports ECA strong desire leave article VII, paragraph 5,
                    unchanged, and accordingly has not submitted NAC suggestion paragraph 5 to
                    Foreign Office. Lapham will telegraph ECA from Shanghai detailed supporting
                    views.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 1149, repeated Shanghai 525.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
